children.comment:
Base class for implementing [Iterable].

This class implements all methods of [Iterable] except [Iterable.iterator]
in terms of `iterator`.
children.name: IterableBase

children.comment: Check whether two references are to the same object.
children.name: identical

children.comment: A parsed URI, as specified by RFC-3986, http://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc3986.
children.name: Uri

children.comment: Creates a new URI object by parsing a URI string.
children.name: parse

children.comment:
Encode the string [component] using percent-encoding to make it
safe for literal use as a URI component.

All characters except uppercase and lowercase letters, digits and
the characters `!$&'()*+,;=:@` are percent-encoded. This is the
set of characters specified in RFC 2396 and the which is
specified for the encodeUriComponent in ECMA-262 version 5.1.

When manually encoding path segments or query components remember
to encode each part separately before building the path or query
string.

For encoding the query part consider using
[encodeQueryComponent].

To avoid the need for explicitly encoding use the [pathSegments]
and [queryParameters] optional named arguments when constructing
a [Uri].
children.name: encodeComponent

children.comment:
Decodes the percent-encoding in [encodedComponent].

Note that decoding a URI component might change its meaning as
some of the decoded characters could be characters with are
delimiters for a given URI componene type. Always split a URI
component using the delimiters for the component before decoding
the individual parts.

For handling the [path] and [query] components consider using
[pathSegments] and [queryParameters] to get the separated and
decoded component.
children.name: decodeComponent

children.comment:
Encode the string [uri] using percent-encoding to make it
safe for literal use as a full URI.

All characters except uppercase and lowercase letters, digits and
the characters `!#$&'()*+,-./:;=?@_~` are percent-encoded. This
is the set of characters specified in in ECMA-262 version 5.1 for
the encodeURI function .
children.name: encodeFull

children.comment:
Decodes the percent-encoding in [uri].

Note that decoding a full URI might change its meaning as some of
the decoded characters could be reserved characters. In most
cases an encoded URI should be parsed into components using
[Uri.parse] before decoding the separate components.
children.name: decodeFull

children.comment:
This is the internal implementation of JavaScript's encodeURI function.
It encodes all characters in the string [text] except for those
that appear in [canonicalTable], and returns the escaped string.
children.name: _uriEncode

children.comment:
Convert a byte (2 character hex sequence) in string [s] starting
at position [pos] to its ordinal value
children.name: _hexCharPairToByte

children.comment:
A JavaScript-like decodeURI function. It unescapes the string [text] and
returns the unescaped string.
children.name: _uriDecode

children.comment:
Returns the authority component.

The authority is formatted from the [userInfo], [host] and [port]
parts.

Returns the empty string if there is no authority component.

Returns 0 if there is no port in the authority component.

Returns the origin of the URI in the form scheme://host:port for the
schemes http and https.

It is an error if the scheme is not "http" or "https".

See: http://www.w3.org/TR/2011/WD-html5-20110405/origin-0.html#origin

children.comment:
Returns the scheme component.

Returns the empty string if there is no scheme component.

Returns the empty string if there is no user info in the
authority component.

Returns the host part of the authority component.

Returns the empty string if there is no authority component and
hence no host.

Returns the path component.

The returned path is encoded. To get direct access to the decoded
path use [pathSegments].

[Iterator] for reading runes (integer Unicode code points) out of a Dart
string.

children.name: _checkSplitSurrogate

children.comment:
Resets the iterator to the rune at the specified index of the string.

Setting a negative [rawIndex], or one greater than or equal to
[:string.length:],
is an error. So is setting it in the middle of a surrogate pair.

Setting the position to the end of then string will set [current] to null.
children.name: rawIndex=

children.comment:
Resets the iterator to the given index into the string.

After this the [current] value is unset.
You must call [moveNext] make the rune at the position current,
or [movePrevious] for the last rune before the position.

Setting a negative [rawIndex], or one greater than [:string.length:],
is an error. So is setting it in the middle of a surrogate pair.
children.name: reset

children.comment:
Returns the starting position of the current rune in the string.

Returns null if the [current] rune is null.
children.name: rawIndex

children.comment:
The rune (integer Unicode code point) starting at the current position in
 the string.
children.name: current

children.comment:
The number of code units comprising the current rune.

Returns zero if there is no current rune ([current] is null).
children.name: currentSize

children.comment:
A string containing the current rune.

For runes outside the basic multilingual plane, this will be
a String of length 2, containing two code units.

Returns null if [current] is null.
children.name: currentAsString

children.comment: String being iterated.
children.name: string

children.comment: Position before the current code point.
children.name: _position

children.comment: Position after the current code point.
children.name: _nextPosition

children.comment:
Current code point.

If the iterator has hit either end, the [_currentCodePoint] is null
and [: _position == _nextPosition :].
children.name: _currentCodePoint

children.comment: Create an iterator positioned at the beginning of the string.
children.name: RuneIterator

children.comment:
Create an iterator positioned before the [index]th code unit of the string.

When created, there is no [current] value.
A [moveNext] will use the rune starting at [index] the current value,
and a [movePrevious] will use the rune ending just before [index] as the
the current value.

It is an error if the [index] position is in the middle of a surrogate
pair.
children.name: RuneIterator.at

children.comment: The runes (integer Unicode code points) of a [String].
children.name: Runes

children.comment:
The String class represents sequences of characters. Strings are
immutable. A string is represented by a sequence of Unicode UTF-16
code units accessible through the [codeUnitAt] or the
[codeUnits] members. Their string representation is accessible through
the index-operator.

The characters of a string are encoded in UTF-16. Decoding UTF-16, which
combines surrogate pairs, yields Unicode code points. Following a similar
terminology to Go we use the name "rune" for an integer representing a
Unicode code point. The runes of a string are accessible through the [runes]
getter.
children.name: String

children.comment:
Gets the character (as a single-code-unit [String]) at the given [index].

The returned string represents exactly one UTF-16 code unit which may be
half of a surrogate pair. For example the Unicode character for a
musical G-clef ("ùÑû") with rune value 0x1D11E consists of a UTF-16 surrogate
pair: `0xD834` and `0xDD1E`. Using the index-operator on this string yields
a String with half of a surrogate pair:

    var clef = "\u{1D11E}";
    clef.length;  // => 2
    clef.runes.first == 0x1D11E;  // => true
    clef.runes.length;  // => 1
    clef.codeUnitAt(0);  // => 0xD834
    clef.codeUnitAt(1);  // => 0xDD1E
    // The following strings are halves of a UTF-16 surrogate pair and
    // thus invalid UTF-16 strings:
    clef[0];  // => a string of length 1 with code-unit value 0xD834.
    clef[1];  // => a string of length 1 with code-unit value 0xDD1E.

This method is equivalent to
`new String.fromCharCode(this.codeUnitAt(index))`.
Returns the 16-bit UTF-16 code unit at the given [index].
children.name: codeUnitAt

children.comment:
Returns whether the two strings are equal.

This method compares each individual code unit of the strings.
Equivalently (for strings that are well-formed UTF-16) it compares each
individual rune (code point).  It does not check for Unicode equivalence.
For example the two following strings both represent the string "Am√©lie"
but, due to their different encoding will not return equal.

    "Am\xe9lie"
    "Ame\u{301}lie"

In the first string the "√©" is encoded as a single unicode code unit (also
a single rune), whereas the second string encodes it as "e" with the
combining accent character "‚óåÃÅ".
Returns whether this string ends with [other].
children.name: endsWith

children.comment: Returns whether this string starts with [other].
children.name: startsWith

children.comment:
Returns the first location of [other] in this string starting at
[start] (inclusive).
Returns -1 if [other] could not be found.
children.name: indexOf

children.comment:
Returns the last location of [other] in this string, searching
backward starting at [start] (inclusive).
Returns -1 if [other] could not be found.
children.name: lastIndexOf

children.comment:
Returns a substring of this string in the given range.
[startIndex] is inclusive and [endIndex] is exclusive.
children.name: substring

children.comment:
Removes leading and trailing whitespace from a string.

If the string contains leading or trailing whitespace a new string with no
leading and no trailing whitespace is returned. Otherwise, the string
itself is returned.

Whitespace is defined by the Unicode White_Space property (as defined in
version 6.2 or later) and the BOM character, 0xFEFF.

Here is the list of trimmed characters (following version 6.2):

    0009..000D    ; White_Space # Cc   <control-0009>..<control-000D>
    0020          ; White_Space # Zs   SPACE
    0085          ; White_Space # Cc   <control-0085>
    00A0          ; White_Space # Zs   NO-BREAK SPACE
    1680          ; White_Space # Zs   OGHAM SPACE MARK
    180E          ; White_Space # Zs   MONGOLIAN VOWEL SEPARATOR
    2000..200A    ; White_Space # Zs   EN QUAD..HAIR SPACE
    2028          ; White_Space # Zl   LINE SEPARATOR
    2029          ; White_Space # Zp   PARAGRAPH SEPARATOR
    202F          ; White_Space # Zs   NARROW NO-BREAK SPACE
    205F          ; White_Space # Zs   MEDIUM MATHEMATICAL SPACE
    3000          ; White_Space # Zs   IDEOGRAPHIC SPACE

    FEFF          ; BOM                ZERO WIDTH NO_BREAK SPACE
children.name: trim

children.comment:
Returns whether this string contains [other] starting
at [startIndex] (inclusive).
children.name: contains

children.comment:
Returns a new string where the first occurence of [from] in this string
is replaced with [to].
children.name: replaceFirst

children.comment:
Returns a new string where all occurences of [from] in this string
are replaced with [replace].
children.name: replaceAll

children.comment:
Returns a new string where all occurences of [from] in this string
are replaced with a [String] depending on [replace].


The [replace] function is called with the [Match] generated
by the pattern, and its result is used as replacement.
children.name: replaceAllMapped

children.comment:
Splits the string around matches of [pattern]. Returns
a list of substrings.

Splitting with an empty string pattern (`""`) splits at UTF-16 code unit
boundaries and not at rune boundaries. The following two expressions
are hence equivalent:

    string.split("")
    string.codeUnits.map((unit) => new String.fromCharCode(unit))

Unless it guaranteed that the string is in the basic multilingual plane
(meaning that each code unit represents a rune) it is often better to
map the runes instead:

    string.runes.map((rune) => new String.fromCharCode(rune))
children.name: split

children.comment:
Splits the string on the [pattern], then converts each part and each match.

The pattern is used to split the string into parts and separating matches.

Each match is converted to a string by calling [onMatch]. If [onMatch]
is omitted, the matched string is used.

Each non-matched part is converted by a call to [onNonMatch]. If
[onNonMatch] is omitted, the non-matching part is used.

Then all the converted parts are combined into the resulting string.
children.name: splitMapJoin

children.comment:
If this string is not already all lower case, returns a new string
where all characters are made lower case. Returns [:this:] otherwise.
children.name: toLowerCase

children.comment:
If this string is not already all upper case, returns a new string
where all characters are made upper case. Returns [:this:] otherwise.
children.name: toUpperCase

children.comment:
The length of the string.

Returns the number of UTF-16 code units in this string. The number
of [runes] might be less, if the string contains characters outside
the basic multilingual plane (plane 0).
children.name: length

children.comment: Returns whether this string is empty.
children.name: isEmpty

children.comment: Returns whether this string is not empty.
children.name: isNotEmpty

children.comment: Returns an unmodifiable list of the UTF-16 code units of this string.
children.name: codeUnits

children.comment:
Returns an iterable of Unicode code-points of this string.

If the string contains surrogate pairs, they will be combined and returned
as one integer by this iterator. Unmatched surrogate halves are treated
like valid 16-bit code-units.
children.name: runes

children.comment:
Allocates a new String for the specified [charCodes].

The [charCodes] can be UTF-16 code units or runes. If a char-code value is
16-bit it is copied verbatim. If it is greater than 16 bits it is
decomposed into a surrogate pair.
children.name: String.fromCharCodes

children.comment:
Allocates a new String for the specified [charCode].

The new string contains a single code unit if the [charCode] can be
represented by a single UTF-16 code unit. Otherwise the [length] is 2 and
the code units form a surrogate pair.

It is allowed (though generally discouraged) to create a String with only
one half of a surrogate pair.
children.name: String.fromCharCode

children.comment: A simple [Stopwatch] interface to measure elapsed time.
children.name: Stopwatch

children.comment:
Starts the [Stopwatch].

The [elapsed] count is increasing monotonically. If the [Stopwatch] has
been stopped, then calling start again restarts it without resetting the
[elapsed] count.

If the [Stopwatch] is currently running, then calling start does nothing.
children.name: start

children.comment:
Stops the [Stopwatch].

The [elapsedTicks] count stops increasing after this call. If the
[Stopwatch] is currently not running, then calling this method has no
effect.
children.name: stop

children.comment:
Resets the [elapsed] count to zero.

This method does not stop or start the [Stopwatch].
children.name: reset

children.comment:
Returns the elapsed number of clock ticks since calling [start] while the
[Stopwatch] is running.

Returns the elapsed number of clock ticks between calling [start] and
calling [stop].

Returns 0 if the [Stopwatch] has never been started.

The elapsed number of clock ticks increases by [frequency] every second.
children.name: elapsedTicks

children.comment: Returns the [elapsedTicks] counter converted to a [Duration].
children.name: elapsed

children.comment: Returns the [elapsedTicks] counter converted to microseconds.
children.name: elapsedMicroseconds

children.comment: Returns the [elapsedTicks] counter converted to milliseconds.
children.name: elapsedMilliseconds

children.comment: Returns the frequency of the elapsed counter in Hz.
children.name: frequency

children.comment: Returns wether the [StopWatch] is currently running.
children.name: isRunning

children.comment:
Creates a [Stopwatch] in stopped state with a zero elapsed count.

The following example shows how to start a [Stopwatch]
immediately after allocation.

    Stopwatch stopwatch = new Stopwatch()..start();
children.name: Stopwatch

children.comment:
An interface implemented by all stack trace objects.

A [StackTrace] is intended to convey information to the user about the call
sequence that triggered an exception.

These objects are created by the runtime, it is not possible to create
them programmatically.
children.name: StackTrace

children.comment:
Returns a [String] representation of the stack trace.

The string represents the full stack trace starting from
the point where a throw ocurred to the top of the current call sequence.

The exact format of the string representation is not final.
children.name: toString

children.comment:
This class is the public interface of a set. A set is a collection
without duplicates.
children.name: Set

children.comment: Returns true if [value] is in the set.
children.name: contains

Adds [value] into the set. The method has no effect if
[value] was already in the set.
children.name: add

Adds all of [elements] to this Set.

Equivalent to adding each element in [elements] using [add],
but some collections may be able to optimize it.
children.name: addAll

children.comment:
Removes [value] from the set. Returns true if [value] was

if [value] value was not in the set.
children.name: remove

children.name: removeAll

Removes all elements of this set that are not
in [elements].
children.name: retainAll

children.name: removeWhere

children.comment: Removes all elements of this set that fail to satisfy [test].

children.name: intersection

children.comment: Returns a new set which contains all the elements of this set and [other].

children.comment:
[RegExp] represents regular expressions.

Dart regular expressions have the same syntax and semantics as
JavaScript regular expressions. See
<http://ecma-international.org/ecma-262/5.1/#sec-15.10>
for the specification of JavaScript regular expressions.

[firstMatch] is the main implementation method that applies a regular
expression to a string and returns the first [Match]. All
other methods in [RegExp] can build on it.

Use [allMatches] to look for all matches of a regular expression in
a string.

The following example finds all matches of a regular expression in
a string.

    RegExp exp = new RegExp(r"(\w+)");
    String str = "Parse my string";
    Iterable<Match> matches = exp.allMatches(str);
children.name: RegExp

children.comment:
Searches for the first match of the regular expression
in the string [str]. Returns `null` if there is no match.
children.name: firstMatch

children.comment:
Returns an iterable on the  matches of the regular
expression in [str].
children.name: allMatches

children.comment: Returns whether the regular expression has a match in the string [str].
children.name: hasMatch

children.comment:
Searches for the first match of the regular expression
in the string [str] and returns the matched string.
children.name: stringMatch

children.comment: The pattern of this regular expression.
children.name: pattern

children.comment: Whether this regular expression matches multiple lines.
children.name: isMultiLine

children.comment: Whether this regular expression is case insensitive.
children.name: isCaseSensitive

children.comment:
Constructs a regular expression. The default implementation of a
[RegExp] sets [multiLine] to false and [caseSensitive] to true.
Throws a [FormatException] if [pattern] is not a valid regular
exression pattern.
children.name: RegExp
Match

children.comment:
Returns the string matched by the given [group]. If [group] is 0,
returns the match of the regular expression.
children.name: group

children.comment:
Returns the strings matched by [groups]. The order in the
returned string follows the order in [groups].
children.name: groups

children.comment: Returns the index in the string where the match starts.
children.name: start

children.comment:
Returns the index in the string after the last character of the
match.
children.name: end

children.comment: Returns the number of groups in the regular expression.
children.name: groupCount

children.comment: The string on which this matcher was computed.
children.name: str

children.comment: The pattern used to search in [str].
children.name: pattern

children.comment: Everything in Dart is an [Object].
children.name: Object

children.comment:
The equality operator.

The default behavior for all [Object]s is to return true if and
only if [:this:] and [other] are the same object.

If a subclass overrides the equality operator it should override
the [hashCode] method as well to maintain consistency.
Returns a string representation of this object.
children.name: toString

children.comment:
[noSuchMethod] is invoked when users invoke a non-existant method
on an object. The name of the method and the arguments of the
invocation are passed to [noSuchMethod] in an [Invocation].
If [noSuchMethod] returns a value, that value becomes the result of
the original invocation.

The default behavior of [noSuchMethod] is to throw a
[noSuchMethodError].
children.name: noSuchMethod

children.comment:
Get a hash code for this object.

All objects have hash codes. Hash codes are guaranteed to be the
same for objects that are equal when compared using the equality
operator [:==:]. Other than that there are no guarantees about
the hash codes. They will not be consistent between runs and
there are no distribution guarantees.

If a subclass overrides [hashCode] it should override the
equality operator as well to maintain consistency.
children.name: hashCode

children.comment: A representation of the runtime type of the object.
children.name: runtimeType

children.comment:
Creates a new [Object] instance.

[Object] instances have no meaningful state, and are only useful
through their identity. An [Object] instance is equal to itself
only.
children.name: Object

children.comment: All numbers in dart are instances of [num].
children.name: num

children.comment: Addition operator.
Subtraction operator.
Multiplication operator.

Euclidean modulo operator.

Returns the remainder of the euclidean division. The euclidean division of
two integers `a` and `b` yields two integers `q` and `r` such that
`a = b*q + r` and `0 <= r < |a|`.

The euclidean division is only defined for integers, but can be easily
extended to work with doubles. In that case `r` may have a non-integer
value, but it still verifies `0 <= r < |a|`.

The sign of the returned value `r` is always positive.

See [remainder] for the remainder of the truncating division.
Division operator.

Truncating division operator.

If either operand is a [double] then the result of the truncating division
[:a ~/ b:] is equivalent to [:(a / b).truncate().toInt():].

If both operands are [int]s then [:a ~/ b:] performs the truncating
integer division.
Negate operator.
children.name: unary-

children.comment:
Return the remainder of the truncating division of `this` by [other].

The result `r` of this operation satisfies: `this = this ~/ other + r`.
As a consequence the remainder `r` has the same sign as the dividend
`this`.
children.name: remainder

children.comment: Relational less than operator.
Relational less than or equal operator.
Relational greater than operator.
Relational greater than or equal operator.
Returns the absolute value of this [num].
children.name: abs

children.comment:
Returns the integer closest to `this`.

Rounds away from zero when there is no closest integer:
 [:(3.5).round() == 4:] and [:(-3.5).round() == -4:].

If `this` is not finite (`NaN` or infinity), throws an [UnsupportedError].
children.name: round

children.comment:
Returns the greatest integer no greater than `this`.

If `this` is not finite (`NaN` or infinity), throws an [UnsupportedError].
children.name: floor

children.comment:
Returns the least integer no smaller than `this`.

If `this` is not finite (`NaN` or infinity), throws an [UnsupportedError].
children.name: ceil

children.comment:
Returns the integer obtained by discarding any fractional
digits from `this`.

If `this` is not finite (`NaN` or infinity), throws an [UnsupportedError].
children.name: truncate

children.comment:
Returns the integer value closest to `this`.

Rounds away from zero when there is no closest integer:
 [:(3.5).round() == 4:] and [:(-3.5).round() == -4:].

The result is a double.
children.name: roundToDouble

children.comment:
Returns the greatest integer value no greater than `this`.

The result is a double.
children.name: floorToDouble

children.comment:
Returns the least integer value no smaller than `this`.

The result is a double.
children.name: ceilToDouble

children.comment:
Returns the integer obtained by discarding any fractional
digits from `this`.

The result is a double.
children.name: truncateToDouble

children.comment:
Clamps [this] to be in the range [lowerLimit]-[upperLimit]. The comparison
is done using [compareTo] and therefore takes [:-0.0:] into account.
It also implies that [double.NAN] is treated as the maximal double value.
children.name: clamp

children.comment: Truncates this [num] to an integer and returns the result as an [int].
children.name: toInt

children.comment:
Return this [num] as a [double].

If the number is not representable as a [double], an
approximation is returned. For numerically large integers, the
approximation may be infinite.
children.name: toDouble

children.comment:
Converts [this] to a string representation with [fractionDigits] digits
after the decimal point.

The parameter [fractionDigits] must be an integer satisfying:
[:0 <= fractionDigits <= 20:].
children.name: toStringAsFixed

children.comment:
Converts [this] to a string in decimal exponential notation with
[fractionDigits] digits after the decimal point.

If [fractionDigits] is given then it must be an integer satisfying:
[:0 <= fractionDigits <= 20:]. Without the parameter the returned string
uses the shortest number of digits that accurately represent [this].
children.name: toStringAsExponential

children.comment:
Converts [this] to a string representation with [precision] significant
digits.

The parameter [precision] must be an integer satisfying:
[:1 <= precision <= 21:].
children.name: toStringAsPrecision

children.comment:
A [Map] is an associative container, mapping a key to a value.
Null values are supported, but null keys are not.
children.name: Map

children.comment: Returns whether this map contains the given [value].
children.name: containsValue

children.comment: Returns whether this map contains the given [key].
children.name: containsKey

children.comment:
Returns the value for the given [key] or null if [key] is not
in the map. Because null values are supported, one should either
use containsKey to distinguish between an absent key and a null
value, or use the [putIfAbsent] method.
Associates the [key] with the given [value].

If [key] is not associated to a value, calls [ifAbsent] and
updates the map by mapping [key] to the value returned by
[ifAbsent]. Returns the value in the map.

It is an error to add or remove keys from map during the call to
[ifAbsent].
children.name: putIfAbsent

children.comment:
Removes the association for the given [key]. Returns the value for
[key] in the map or null if [key] is not in the map. Note that values
can be null and a returned null value does not always imply that the
key is absent.
children.name: remove

children.comment: Removes all pairs from the map.
children.name: clear

children.comment:
Applies [f] to each {key, value} pair of the map.

It is an error to add or remove keys from the map during iteration.
children.name: forEach

children.comment: The keys of [this].
children.name: keys

children.comment: The values of [this].
children.name: values

children.comment: The number of {key, value} pairs in the map.
children.name: length

children.comment: Returns true if there is no {key, value} pair in the map.
children.name: isEmpty

children.comment: Returns true if there is at least one {key, value} pair in the map.
children.name: isNotEmpty

children.comment: Creates a map with the default implementation.
children.name: Map

children.comment: Creates a [Map] that contains all key value pairs of [other].
children.name: Map.from

children.comment:
A [List] is an indexable collection with a length.

A `List` implementation can choose not to support all methods
of the `List` interface.

The most common list types are:
* Fixed length list. It is an error to use operations that can change
  the list's length.
* Growable list. Full implementation of the interface.
* Unmodifiable list. It is an error to use operations that can change
  the list's length, or that can change the values of the list.
  If an unmodifable list is backed by another modifiable data structure,
  the values read from it may still change over time.

Example:

    var fixedLengthList = new List(5);
    fixedLengthList.length = 0;  // throws.
    fixedLengthList.add(499);  // throws
    fixedLengthList[0] = 87;
    var growableList = [1, 2];
    growableList.length = 0;
    growableList.add(499);
    growableList[0] = 87;
    var unmodifiableList = const [1, 2];
    unmodifiableList.length = 0;  // throws.
    unmodifiableList.add(499);  // throws
    unmodifiableList[0] = 87;  // throws.

Lists are [Iterable].
List iteration iterates over values in index order.
Changing the values will not affect iteration,
but changing the valid indices -
that is, changing the list's length -
between iteration steps
will cause a [ConcurrentModificationError].
This means that only growable lists can throw [ConcurrentModificationError].
If the length changes temporarily
and is restored before continuing the iteration,
the iterator will not detect it.
children.name: List

children.comment:
Returns the element at the given [index] in the list or throws
an [RangeError] if [index] is out of bounds.

Sets the entry at the given [index] in the list to [value].

Throws an [RangeError] if [index] is out of bounds.

Changes the length of the list. If [newLength] is greater than
the current [length], entries are initialized to [:null:].

Throws an [UnsupportedError] if the list is not extendable.
children.name: length=

children.comment:
Adds [value] at the end of the list, extending the length by
one.

Throws an [UnsupportedError] if the list is not extendable.
children.name: add

children.comment:
Appends all elements of the [iterable] to the end of this list.

Extends the length of the list by the number of elements in [iterable].
Throws an [UnsupportedError] if this list is not extensible.
children.name: addAll

children.comment:
Sorts the list according to the order specified by the [compare] function.

The [compare] function must act as a [Comparator].

The default [List] implementations use [Comparable.compare] if
[compare] is omitted.
children.name: sort

children.comment:
Returns the first index of [element] in the list.

Searches the list from index [start] to the length of the list.
The first time an element [:e:] is encountered so that [:e == element:],
the index of [:e:] is returned.
Returns -1 if [element] is not found.
children.name: indexOf

children.comment:
Returns the last index of [element] in the list.

Searches the list backwards from index [start] (inclusive) to 0.

The first time an element [:e:] is encountered so that [:e == element:],
the index of [:e:] is returned.

If start is not provided, it defaults to [:this.length - 1:].

Returns -1 if [element] is not found.
children.name: lastIndexOf

children.comment:
Removes all elements in the list.

The length of the list becomes zero.

Throws an [UnsupportedError], and retains all elements, if the
length of the list cannot be changed.
children.name: clear

children.comment:
Inserts the element at position [index] in the list.

This increases the length of the list by one and shifts all elements
at or after the index towards the end of the list.

It is an error if the [index] does not point inside the list or at the
position after the last element.
children.name: insert

children.comment:
Inserts all elements of [iterable] at position [index] in the list.

This increases the length of the list by the length of [iterable] and
shifts all later elements towards the end of the list.

It is an error if the [index] does not point inside the list or at the
position after the last element.
children.name: insertAll

children.comment:
Overwrites elements of `this` with the elemenst of [iterable] starting
at position [index] in the list.

This operation does not increase the length of `this`.

It is an error if the [index] does not point inside the list or at the
position after the last element.

It is an error if the [iterable] is longer than [length] - [index].
children.name: setAll

children.comment:
Removes [value] from the list. Returns true if [value] was
in the list. Returns false otherwise. The method has no effect
if [value] value was not in the list.
children.name: remove

children.comment:
Removes the element at position [index] from the list.

This reduces the length of `this` by one and moves all later elements
down by one position.

Returns the removed element.

Throws an [ArgumentError] if [index] is not an [int].

Throws an [RangeError] if the [index] does not point inside
the list.

Throws an [UnsupportedError], and doesn't remove the element,
if the length of `this` cannot be changed.
children.name: removeAt

children.comment:
Pops and returns the last element of the list.
Throws a [UnsupportedError] if the length of the
list cannot be changed.
children.name: removeLast

children.comment:
Removes all elements of this list that satisfy [test].

An elements [:e:] satisfies [test] if [:test(e):] is true.
children.name: removeWhere

children.comment:
Removes all elements of this list that fail to satisfy [test].

An elements [:e:] satisfies [test] if [:test(e):] is true.
children.name: retainWhere

children.comment:
Returns a new list containing the elements from [start] to [end].

If [end] is omitted, the [length] of `this` is used.

It is an error if [start] or [end] are not indices into `this`,
or if [end] is before [start].
children.name: sublist

children.comment:
Returns an [Iterable] that iterators over the elements in the range
[start] to [end] exclusive. The result of this function
is backed by `this`.

It is an error if [end] is before [start].

It is an error if the [start] and [end] are not valid ranges at the time
of the call to this method. The returned [Iterable] behaves similar to
`skip(start).take(end - start)`. That is, it will not throw exceptions
if `this` changes size.

Example:

    var list = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5];
    var range = list.getRange(1, 4);
    print(range.join(', '));  // => 2, 3, 4
    list.length = 3;
    print(range.join(', '));  // => 2, 3
children.name: getRange

children.comment:
Copies the elements of [iterable], skipping the [skipCount] first elements,
into the range [start] to [end] exclusive of `this`.

If [start] equals [end] and [start]..[end] represents a legal range, this
method has no effect.

It is an error if [start]..[end] is not a valid range pointing into the
`this`.

It is an error if the [iterable] does not have enough elements after
skipping [skipCount] elements.

Example:

    var list = [1, 2, 3, 4];
    var list2 = [5, 6, 7, 8, 9];
    list.setRange(1, 3, list2, 3);
    print(list);  // => [1, 8, 9, 4]
children.name: setRange

children.comment:
Removes the elements in the range [start] to [end] exclusive.

It is an error if [start]..[end] is not a valid range pointing into the
`this`.
children.name: removeRange

children.comment:
Sets the elements in the range [start] to [end] exclusive to the given
[fillValue].

It is an error if [start]..[end] is not a valid range pointing into the
`this`.
children.name: fillRange

children.comment:
Removes the elements in the range [start] to [end] exclusive and replaces
them with the contents of the [iterable].

It is an error if [start]..[end] is not a valid range pointing into the
`this`.

Example:

    var list = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5];
    list.replaceRange(1, 3, [6, 7, 8, 9]);
    print(list);  // [1, 6, 7, 8, 9, 4, 5]
children.name: replaceRange

children.comment:
Returns an unmodifiable [Map] view of `this`.

It has the indices of this list as keys, and the corresponding elements
as values.
children.name: asMap

children.comment:
Returns the number of elements in the list.

The valid indices for a list are 0 through `length - 1`.
children.name: length

children.comment: Returns an [Iterable] of the elements of this [List] in reverse order.
children.name: reversed

children.comment:
Creates a list of the given [length].

The list is a fixed-length list if [length] is provided, and an empty
growable list if [length] is omitted.

It is an error if [length] is not a non-negative integer.
children.name: List

children.comment:
Creates a fixed-length list of the given [length] where each entry
contains [fill].
children.name: List.filled

children.comment:
Creates an list with the elements of [other].

The order in the list will be
the order provided by the iterator of [other].

The returned list is growable if [growable] is true, otherwise it's
a fixed length list.
children.name: List.from

children.comment:
Generate a `List` of values.

Creates a list with [length] positions
and fills them by values created by calling [generator]
for each index in the range `0` .. `[length] - 1`
in increasing order.

The created list's length is fixed unless [growable] is true.
children.name: List.generate

children.comment:
The [Iterator] class provides methods to iterate over an object. It
is transparently used by the for-in construct to test for the end
of the iteration, and to get the elements.

If the object iterated over is changed during the iteration, the
behavior is unspecified.

The [Iterator] is initially positioned before the first element. Before
accessing the first element the iterator must thus be advanced ([moveNext])
to point to the first element. If there is no element left, then [moveNext]
returns false.

A typical usage of an [Iterator] looks as follows:

    var it = obj.iterator;
    while (it.moveNext()) {
      use(it.current);
    }
children.name: Iterator

children.comment:
Moves to the next element. Returns true if [current] contains the next
element. Returns false, if no element was left.

It is safe to invoke [moveNext] even when the iterator is already
positioned after the last element. In this case [moveNext] has no effect.
children.name: moveNext

children.comment:
Returns the current element.

Return [:null:] if the iterator has not yet been moved to the first
element, or if the iterator has been moved after the last element of the
[Iterable].
children.name: current

children.comment: An [Iterator] that allows moving backwards as well as forwards.
children.name: BidirectionalIterator

children.comment:
Move back to the previous element.

Returns true and updates [current] if successful. Returns false
and sets [current] to null if there is no previous element.
children.name: movePrevious

children.comment:
The [Iterable] interface allows to get an [Iterator] out of an
[Iterable] object.

This interface is used by the for-in construct to iterate over an
[Iterable] object.
The for-in construct takes an [Iterable] object at the right-hand
side, and calls its [iterator] method to get an [Iterator] on it.

A user-defined class that implements the [Iterable] interface can
be used as the right-hand side of a for-in construct.
children.name: Iterable

children.comment:
Returns a lazy [Iterable] where each element [:e:] of `this` is replaced
by the result of [:f(e):].

This method returns a view of the mapped elements. As long as the
returned [Iterable] is not iterated over, the supplied function [f] will
not be invoked. The transformed elements will not be cached. Iterating
multiple times over the the returned [Iterable] will invoke the supplied
function [f] multiple times on the same element.
children.name: map

children.comment:
Returns a lazy [Iterable] with all elements that satisfy the
predicate [test].

This method returns a view of the mapped elements. As long as the
returned [Iterable] is not iterated over, the supplied function [test] will
not be invoked. Iterating will not cache results, and thus iterating
multiple times over the the returned [Iterable] will invoke the supplied
function [test] multiple times on the same element.
children.name: where

children.comment:
Expand each element of this [Iterable] into zero or more elements.

The resulting Iterable will run through the elements returned
by [f] for each element of this, in order.

The returned [Iterable] is lazy, and will call [f] for each element
of this every time it's iterated.
children.name: expand

children.comment: Check whether the collection contains an element equal to [element].
children.name: contains

children.comment: Applies the function [f] to each element of this collection.
children.name: forEach

children.comment:
Reduces a collection to a single value by iteratively combining elements
of the collection using the provided function.

Example of calculating the sum of an iterable:

    iterable.reduce((value, element) => value + element);
children.name: reduce

children.comment:
Reduces a collection to a single value by iteratively combining each
element of the collection with an existing value using the provided
function.

Use [initialValue] as the initial value, and the function [combine] to
create a new value from the previous one and an element.

Example of calculating the sum of an iterable:

    iterable.fold(0, (prev, element) => prev + element);
children.name: fold

children.comment:
Returns true if every elements of this collection satisify the
predicate [test]. Returns `false` otherwise.
children.name: every

children.comment:
Converts each element to a [String] and concatenates the strings.

Converts each element to a [String] by calling [Object.toString] on it.
Then concatenates the strings, optionally separated by the [separator]
string.
children.name: join

children.comment:
Returns true if one element of this collection satisfies the
predicate [test]. Returns false otherwise.
children.name: any

children.comment:
Creates a [List] containing the elements of this [Iterable].

The elements will be in iteration order. The list is fixed-length
if [growable] is false.
children.name: toList

children.comment: Creates a [Set] containing the elements of this [Iterable].
children.name: toSet

children.comment:
Returns an [Iterable] with at most [n] elements.

The returned [Iterable] may contain fewer than [n] elements, if `this`
contains fewer than [n] elements.
children.name: take

children.comment:
Returns an [Iterable] that stops once [test] is not satisfied anymore.

The filtering happens lazily. Every new [Iterator] of the returned
[Iterable] will start iterating over the elements of `this`.

When the iterator encounters an element `e` that does not satisfy [test],
it discards `e` and moves into the finished state. That is, it will not
ask or provide any more elements.
children.name: takeWhile

children.comment:
Returns an [Iterable] that skips the first [n] elements.

If `this` has fewer than [n] elements, then the resulting [Iterable] will
be empty.
children.name: skip

children.comment:
Returns an [Iterable] that skips elements while [test] is satisfied.

The filtering happens lazily. Every new [Iterator] of the returned
[Iterable] will iterate over all elements of `this`.

As long as the iterator's elements do not satisfy [test] they are
discarded. Once an element satisfies the [test] the iterator stops testing
and uses every element unconditionally. That is, the elements of the
returned [Iterable] are the elements of `this` starting from the first
element that doesn't satisfy [test].
children.name: skipWhile

children.comment:
Returns the first element that satisfies the given predicate [test].

If none matches, the result of invoking the [orElse] function is
returned. By default, when [orElse] is `null`, a [StateError] is
thrown.
children.name: firstWhere

children.comment:
Returns the last element that satisfies the given predicate [test].

If none matches, the result of invoking the [orElse] function is
returned. By default, when [orElse] is `null`, a [StateError] is
thrown.
children.name: lastWhere

children.comment:
Returns the single element that satisfies [test]. If no or more than one
element match then a [StateError] is thrown.
children.name: singleWhere

children.comment:
Returns the [index]th element.

If `this` has fewer than [index] elements throws a [RangeError].

Note: if `this` does not have a deterministic iteration order then the
function may simply return any element without any iteration if there are
at least [index] elements in `this`.
children.name: elementAt

children.comment: Returns an [Iterator] that iterates over this [Iterable] object.
children.name: iterator

children.comment:
Returns the number of elements in [this].

Counting all elements may be involve running through all elements and can
therefore be slow.
children.name: length

children.comment: Returns true if there is no element in this collection.
children.name: isEmpty

children.comment: Returns true if there is at least one element in this collection.
children.name: isNotEmpty

children.comment:
Returns the first element.

If `this` is empty throws a [StateError]. Otherwise this method is
equivalent to [:this.elementAt(0):]
children.name: first

children.comment:
Returns the last element.

If `this` is empty throws a [StateError].
children.name: last

children.comment:
Returns the single element in `this`.

If `this` is empty or has more than one element throws a [StateError].
children.name: single

children.comment:
Create an [Iterable] that generates its elements dynamically.

The [Iterators] created by the [Iterable] will count from
zero to [:count - 1:] while iterating, and call [generator]
with that index to create the next value.

As an [Iterable], [:new Iterable.generate(n, generator)):] is equivalent to
[:const [0, ..., n - 1].map(generator):]
children.name: Iterable.generate

children.comment:
Representation of the invocation of a member on an object.

This is the type of objects passed to [Object.noSuchMethod] when
an object doesn't support the member invocation that was attempted
on it.
children.name: Invocation

children.comment: The name of the invoked member.
children.name: memberName

children.comment: An unmodifiable view of the positional arguments of the call.
children.name: positionalArguments

children.comment: An unmodifiable view of the named arguments of the call.
children.name: namedArguments

children.comment: Whether the invocation was a method call.
children.name: isMethod

children.comment:
Whether the invocation was a getter call.
If so, both types of arguments will be null.
children.name: isGetter

children.comment:
Whether the invocation was a setter call.

If so, [arguments] will have exactly one positonal argument,
and namedArguments will be null.
children.name: isSetter

children.comment: Whether the invocation was a getter or a setter call.
children.name: isAccessor

children.comment:
Representation of Dart integers containing integer specific
operations and specialization of operations inherited from [num].

Integers can be arbitrarily large in Dart.

*Note however, that when compiling to JavaScript, integers are
implemented as JavaScript numbers. When compiling to JavaScript,
integers are therefore restricted to 53 significant bits because
all JavaScript numbers are double-precision floating point
values. The behavior of the operators and methods in the [int]
class therefore sometimes differs between the Dart VM and Dart code
compiled to JavaScript.*
children.name: int

children.comment: The bit-wise and operator.
The bit-wise or operator.
The bit-wise xor operator.
The bit-wise negate operator.
The left shift operator.
The right shift operator.
Negate operator. Negating an integer produces an integer.
children.name: unary-

children.comment: Returns the absolute value of this integer.
children.name: abs

children.comment: Returns `this`.
children.name: round

children.comment: Returns `this`.
children.name: floor

children.comment: Returns [this].
children.name: ceil

children.comment: Returns [this].
children.name: truncate

children.comment: Returns `this.toDouble()`.
children.name: roundToDouble

children.comment: Returns `this.toDouble()`.
children.name: floorToDouble

children.comment: Returns `this.toDouble()`.
children.name: ceilToDouble

children.comment: Returns `this.toDouble()`.
children.name: truncateToDouble

children.comment:
Returns a representation of this [int] value.

It should always be the case that if [:i:] is an [int] value,
then [:i == int.parse(i.toString()):].
children.name: toString

children.comment:
Converts [this] to a string representation in the given [radix].

In the string representation, lower-case letters are used for digits above
'9'.

The [radix] argument must be an integer in the range 2 to 36.
children.name: toRadixString

children.comment:
Parse [source] as an integer literal and return its value.

The [radix] must be in the range 2..36. The digits used are
first the decimal digits 0..9, and then the letters 'a'..'z'.
Accepts capital letters as well.

If no [radix] is given then it defaults to 16 if the string starts
with "0x", "-0x" or "+0x" and 10 otherwise.

The [source] must be a non-empty sequence of base-[radix] digits,
optionally prefixed with a minus or plus sign ('-' or '+').

It must always be the case for an int [:n:] and radix [:r:] that
[:n == parseRadix(n.toRadixString(r), r):].

If the [source] is not a valid integer literal, optionally prefixed by a
sign, the [onError] is called with the [source] as argument, and its return
value is used instead. If no [onError] is provided, a [FormatException]
is thrown.
children.name: parse

children.comment: Returns true if and only if this integer is even.
children.name: isEven

children.comment: Returns true if and only if this integer is odd.
children.name: isOdd

children.comment:
Super-type of all function types.

A function value, or an instance of a class with a "call" method, is a
subtype of a function type, and as such, a subtype of [Function].
children.name: Function

children.comment:
Dynamically call [function] with the specified arguments.

Acts the same as calling function with positional arguments
corresponding to the elements of [positionalArguments] and
named arguments corresponding to the elements of [namedArguments].

This includes giving the same errors if [function] isn't callable or
if it expects different parameters.

Example: [:
Map<Symbol, dynamic> namedArguments = new Map<Symbol, dynamic>();
namedArguments[const Symbol("f")] = 4;
namedArguments[const Symbol("g")] = 5;
Function.apply(foo, [1,2,3], namedArguments); :]
gives exactly the same result as [: foo(1, 2, 3, f: 4, g: 5) :].

If [positionalArguments] is null, it's considered an empty list.
If [namedArguments] is omitted or null, it is considered an empty map.
children.name: apply

children.comment: An [Expando] allows adding new properties to objects.
children.name: Expando

children.comment: Expando toString method override.
children.name: toString

children.comment:
Gets the value of this [Expando]'s property on the given
object. If the object hasn't been expanded, the method returns
[null].

Sets the value of this [Expando]'s property on the given
object. Properties can effectively be removed again by setting
their value to null.

The name of the this [Expando] as passed to the constructor. If
no name was passed to the constructor, the name is [null].
children.name: name

children.comment:
Creates a new [Expando]. The optional name is only used for
debugging purposes and creating two different [Expando]s with the
same name yields two [Expando]s that work on different properties
of the objects they are used on.
children.name: Expando

children.comment:
Exception thrown when a string or some other data does not have an expected
format and cannot be parsed or processed.
children.name: FormatException

children.comment: A message describing the format error.
children.name: message

children.comment: Creates a new FormatException with an optional error [message].
children.name: FormatException

children.comment: Default implementation of [Exception] which carries a message.
children.name: _ExceptionImplementation

children.comment:
A marker interface implemented by all core library exceptions.

An [Exception] is intended to convey information to the user about a failure,
so that the error can be addressed programmatically. It is intended to be
caught, and it should contain useful data fields.

Creating instances of [Exception] directly with [:new Exception("message"):]
is discouraged, and only included as a temporary measure during development,
until the actual exceptions used by a library are done.
children.name: Exception

children.comment: Error thrown when a runtime error occurs.
children.name: RuntimeError

children.comment:
Error occurring when a collection is modified during iteration.

Some modifications may be allowed for some collections, so each collection
([Iterable] or similar collection of values) should declare which operations
are allowed during an iteration.
children.name: ConcurrentModificationError

children.comment: The object that was modified in an incompatible way.
children.name: modifiedObject

children.comment:
The operation was not allowed by the current state of the object.

This is a generic error used for a variety of different erroneous
actions. The message should be descriptive.
children.name: StateError

children.comment:
Thrown by operations that have not been implemented yet.

This [Error] is thrown by unfinished code that hasn't yet implemented
all the features it needs.

If a class is not intending to implement the feature, it should throw
an [UnsupportedError] instead. This error is only intended for
use during development.
children.name: UnimplementedError

children.comment:
The operation was not allowed by the object.

This [Error] is thrown when an instance cannot implement one of the methods
in its signature.
children.name: UnsupportedError

children.comment: Error thrown by the default implementation of [:noSuchMethod:] on [Object].
children.name: NoSuchMethodError

children.comment:
Create a [NoSuchMethodError] corresponding to a failed method call.

The first parameter to this constructor is the receiver of the method call.
That is, the object on which the method was attempted called.
The second parameter is the name of the called method or accessor.
The third parameter is a list of the positional arguments that the method
was called with.
The fourth parameter is a map from [String] names to the values of named
arguments that the method was called with.
The optional [exisitingArgumentNames] is the expected parameters of a
method with the same name on the receiver, if available. This is
the method that would have been called if the parameters had matched.
children.name: NoSuchMethodError

children.comment:
Error thrown when control reaches the end of a switch case.

The Dart specification requires this error to be thrown when
control reaches the end of a switch case (except the last case
of a switch) without meeting a break or similar end of the control
flow.
children.name: FallThroughError

children.comment: Error thrown because of an index outside of the valid range.
children.name: RangeError

children.comment:
Create a new [RangeError] with the given [message].

Temporarily made const for backwards compatibilty.
children.name: RangeError

children.comment: Create a new [RangeError] with a message for the given [value].
children.name: RangeError.value

children.comment: Create a new [RangeError] with a message for a value and a range.
children.name: RangeError.range

children.comment: Error thrown when a function is passed an unacceptable argument.
children.name: ArgumentError

children.comment: The [message] describes the erroneous argument.
children.name: ArgumentError

children.comment: Error thrown when attempting to throw [:null:].
children.name: NullThrownError

children.comment: Error thrown by the runtime system when a cast operation fails.
children.name: CastError

children.comment: Error thrown by the runtime system when a type assertion fails.
children.name: TypeError

children.comment: Error thrown by the runtime system when an assert statement fails.
children.name: AssertionError

children.comment:
Safely convert a value to a [String] description.

The conversion is guaranteed to not throw, so it won't use the object's
toString method.
children.name: safeToString

children.comment: A [Duration] represents a time span. A duration can be negative.
children.name: Duration

children.comment: Returns the sum of this [Duration] and [other]  as a new [Duration].

Returns the difference of this [Duration] and [other] as a new
[Duration].

Multiplies this [Duration] by the given [factor] and returns the result
as a new [Duration].

Divides this [Duration] by the given [quotient] and returns the truncated
result as a new [Duration].

Throws an [IntegerDivisionByZeroException] if [quotient] is `0`.
This [Duration] in days. Incomplete days are discarded
children.name: inDays

children.comment:
This [Duration] in hours. Incomplete hours are discarded.

The returned value can be greater than 23.
children.name: inHours

children.comment:
This [Duration] in minutes. Incomplete minutes are discarded.

The returned value can be greater than 59.
children.name: inMinutes

children.comment:
This [Duration] in seconds. Incomplete seconds are discarded.

The returned value can be greater than 59.
children.name: inSeconds

children.comment:
This [Duration] in milliseconds. Incomplete milliseconds are discarded.

The returned value can be greater than 999.
children.name: inMilliseconds

children.comment: This [Duration] in microseconds.
children.name: inMicroseconds

children.comment: This [Duration] in microseconds.
children.name: _duration

children.comment:
The duration is the sum of all individual parts. This means that individual
parts don't need to be less than the next-bigger unit. For example [hours]
is allowed to have a value greater than 23.

All individual parts are allowed to be negative.
All arguments are by default 0.
children.name: Duration

children.comment:
Representation of Dart doubles containing double specific constants
and operations and specializations of operations inherited from
[num].

The [double] type is contagious. Operations on [double]s return
[double] results.
children.name: double

children.comment: Addition operator.
Subtraction operator.
Multiplication operator.
Division operator.

Truncating division operator.

The result of the truncating division [:a ~/ b:] is equivalent to
[:(a / b).truncate():].
Negate operator.
children.name: unary-

children.comment: Returns the absolute value of this [double].
children.name: abs

children.comment:
Returns the integer closest to `this`.

Rounds away from zero when there is no closest integer:
 [:(3.5).round() == 4:] and [:(-3.5).round() == -4:].

If `this` is not finite (`NaN` or infinity), throws an [UnsupportedError].
children.name: round

children.comment:
Returns the greatest integer no greater than `this`.

If `this` is not finite (`NaN` or infinity), throws an [UnsupportedError].
children.name: floor

children.comment:
Returns the least integer no smaller than `this`.

If `this` is not finite (`NaN` or infinity), throws an [UnsupportedError].
children.name: ceil

children.comment:
Returns the integer obtained by discarding any fractional
digits from `this`.

If `this` is not finite (`NaN` or infinity), throws an [UnsupportedError].
children.name: truncate

children.comment:
Returns the integer value, as a double, closest to `this`.

Rounds away from zero when there is no closest integer:
 [:(3.5).round() == 4:] and [:(-3.5).round() == -4:].
children.name: roundToDouble

children.comment:
Returns the greatest integer value no greater than `this`.

The result is a double.
children.name: floorToDouble

children.comment:
Returns the least integer value no smaller than `this`.

The result is a double.
children.name: ceilToDouble

children.comment:
Returns the integer obtained by discarding any fractional
digits from `this`.

The result is a double.
children.name: truncateToDouble

children.comment:
Provide a representation of this [double] value.

The representation is a number literal such that the closest double value
to the representation's mathematical value is this [double].

Returns "NaN" for the Not-a-Number value.
Returns "Infinity" and "-Infinity" for positive and negative Infinity.
Returns "-0.0" for negative zero.

It should always be the case that if [:d:] is a [double], then
[:d == double.parse(d.toString()):].
children.name: toString

children.comment:
Parse [source] as an double literal and return its value.

Accepts an optional sign (`+` or `-`) followed by either the characters
"Infinity", the characters "NaN" or a floating-point representation.
A floating-point representation is composed of a mantissa and an optional
exponent part. The mantissa is either a decimal point (`.`) followed by a
sequence of (decimal) digits, or a sequence of digits
optionally followed by a decimal point and optionally more digits. The
(optional) exponent part consists of the character "e" or "E", an optional
sign, and one or more digits.

The input string is trimmed (see [String.trim]) before conversion.

If the [source] is not a valid double literal, the [handleError]
is called with the [source] as argument, and its return value is
used instead. If no handleError is provided, a [FormatException]
is thrown.

Examples of accepted strings:

    "3.14"
    "  3.14 \xA0"
    "0."
    ".0"
    "-1.e3"
    "1234E+7"
    "+.12e-9"
    "-NaN"
children.name: parse

children.comment:
A DateTime object represents a point in time.

It can represent time values that are at a distance of at most
8,640,000,000,000,000ms (100,000,000 days) from epoch (1970-01-01 UTC). In
other words: [:millisecondsSinceEpoch.abs() <= 8640000000000000:].

Also see [Stopwatch] for means to measure time-spans.
children.name: DateTime

children.comment:
Constructs a new [DateTime] instance based on [formattedString].

The function parses a subset of ISO 8601. Examples of accepted strings:

* `"2012-02-27 13:27:00"`
* `"2012-02-27 13:27:00.123456z"`
* `"20120227 13:27:00"`
* `"20120227T132700"`
* `"20120227"`
* `"+20120227"`
* `"2012-02-27T14Z"`
* `"-123450101 00:00:00 Z"`: in the year -12345.
children.name: parse

children.comment:
Returns true if [other] is a [DateTime] at the same moment and in the
same timezone (UTC or local).

See [isAtSameMomentAs] for a comparison that ignores the timezone.

Returns true if [this] occurs before [other]. The comparison is independent
of whether the time is in UTC or in the local time zone.
children.name: isBefore

children.comment:
Returns true if [this] occurs after [other]. The comparison is independent
of whether the time is in UTC or in the local time zone.
children.name: isAfter

children.comment:
Returns true if [this] occurs at the same moment as [other]. The
comparison is independent of whether the time is in UTC or in the local
time zone.
children.name: isAtSameMomentAs

children.comment:
Returns [this] in the local time zone. Returns itself if it is already in
the local time zone. Otherwise, this method is equivalent to

    new DateTime.fromMillisecondsSinceEpoch(millisecondsSinceEpoch,
                                            isUtc: false)
children.name: toLocal

children.comment:
Returns [this] in UTC. Returns itself if it is already in UTC. Otherwise,
this method is equivalent to

    new DateTime.fromMillisecondsSinceEpoch(millisecondsSinceEpoch,
                                            isUtc: true)
children.name: toUtc

children.comment:
Returns a human readable string for this instance.
The returned string is constructed for the time zone of this instance.
children.name: toString

children.comment: Returns a new [DateTime] with the [duration] added to [this].
children.name: add

children.comment: Returns a new [DateTime] with the [duration] subtracted from [this].
children.name: subtract

children.comment: Returns a [Duration] with the difference of [this] and [other].
children.name: difference

children.comment:
Returns the abbreviated time-zone name.

Examples: [:"CET":] or [:"CEST":].
children.name: timeZoneName

children.comment:
The time-zone offset is the difference between local time and UTC. That is,
the offset is positive for time zones west of UTC.

Note, that JavaScript, Python and C return the difference between UTC and
local time. Java, C# and Ruby return the difference between local time and
UTC.
children.name: timeZoneOffset

children.comment: Returns the year.
children.name: year

children.comment: Returns the month into the year [1..12].
children.name: month

children.comment: Returns the day into the month [1..31].
children.name: day

children.comment: Returns the hour into the day [0..23].
children.name: hour

children.comment: Returns the minute into the hour [0...59].
children.name: minute

children.comment: Returns the second into the minute [0...59].
children.name: second

children.comment: Returns the millisecond into the second [0...999].
children.name: millisecond

children.comment:
Returns the week day [MON..SUN]. In accordance with ISO 8601
a week starts with Monday which has the value 1.
children.name: weekday

children.comment:
The milliseconds since 1970-01-01T00:00:00Z (UTC). This value is
independent of the time zone.

See [Stopwatch] for means to measure time-spans.
children.name: millisecondsSinceEpoch

children.comment: True if this [DateTime] is set to UTC time.
children.name: isUtc

children.comment:
Constructs a [DateTime] instance based on the individual parts. The date is
in the local time zone.

[month] and [day] are one-based. For example
[:new DateTime(1938, 1, 10):] represents the 10th of January 1938.
children.name: DateTime

children.comment:
Constructs a [DateTime] instance based on the individual parts. The date is
in the UTC time zone.

[month] and [day] are one-based. For example
[:new DateTime.utc(1938, 1, 10):] represents the 10th of January 1938 in
Coordinated Universal Time.
children.name: DateTime.utc

children.comment:
Constructs a new [DateTime] instance with current date time value in the
local time zone.
children.name: DateTime.now

children.comment:
Constructs a new [DateTime] instance with the given [millisecondsSinceEpoch].
If [isUtc] is false then the date is in the local time zone.

The constructed [DateTime] represents
1970-01-01T00:00:00Z + [millisecondsSinceEpoch]ms in the given
time zone (local or UTC).
children.name: DateTime.fromMillisecondsSinceEpoch

children.comment: Interface used by types that have an intrinsic ordering.
children.name: Comparable

children.comment:
Compares this object to another [Comparable]

Returns a value like a [Comparator] when comparing [:this:] to [other].

May throw an [ArgumentError] if [other] is of a type that
is not comparable to [:this:].
children.name: compareTo

children.comment:
Compare one comparable to another.

This utility function is used as the default comparator
for the [List] sort function.
children.name: compare

children.comment:
The signature of a generic comparison function.

A comparison function represents an ordering on a type of objects.
A total ordering on a type means that for two values, either they
are equal or one is greater than the other (and the latter must then be
smaller than the former).

A [Comparator] function represents such a total ordering by returning

* a negative integer if [a] is smaller than [b],
* zero if [a] is equal to [b], and
* a positive integer if [a] is greater than [b].
children.name: Comparator
